      <div class="nr-content">

        <article class="nr-featured" aria-label="Featured resource">
          <span class="nr-featured-badge">Key Document</span>
          <h2 class="nr-featured-title">Level Up Media Guidelines for Reporting Fatal Domestic Abuse</h2>
          <p class="nr-featured-desc">The UK's first media guidelines on reporting domestic abuse deaths, endorsed by both IPSO and IMPRESS. Built around the AIDA framework — Accountability, Images, Dignity, Accuracy — and used in CPD-accredited training for over 500 journalists.</p>
          <a href="https://welevelup.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/Media-Guidelines-V2-1.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nr-featured-btn">Download PDF →</a>
        </article>

        <ol class="nr-list" aria-label="All campaign resources">

          <li class="nr-resource-item" data-tags="guidance campaign" data-source="level-up" data-type="guidelines" data-topic="domestic-abuse media-reporting aida ddw journalism-standards">
            <span class="nr-item-num">01</span>
            <div class="nr-item-body">
              <div class="nr-item-tags"><span class="nr-topic">Media Reporting</span><span class="nr-topic">AIDA Framework</span><span class="nr-topic">DDW Campaign</span><span class="nr-topic">Journalism Standards</span></div>
              <h3 class="nr-item-title"><a href="https://welevelup.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/Media-Guidelines-V2-1.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Level Up Media Guidelines for Reporting Fatal Domestic Abuse (v2)</a></h3>
              <p class="nr-item-meta">Level Up · 2022</p>
              <p class="nr-item-abstract">The second edition of Level Up's landmark media guidelines — the UK's first evidence-based guidance for journalists on how to report domestic abuse deaths accurately and with dignity. Structured around the AIDA framework (Accountability, Images, Dignity, Accuracy), the guidelines are endorsed by both press regulators IPSO and IMPRESS, and have been distributed to every newsroom in the country. They form the basis of Level Up's CPD-accredited journalist training programme, attended by over 500 journalists to date.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="nr-item-end"><span class="nr-type-badge nr-type-badge--focused">Guidelines</span><a href="https://welevelup.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/Media-Guidelines-V2-1.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nr-item-link" aria-label="Open resource">↗</a></div>
          </li>

          <li class="nr-resource-item" data-tags="campaign regulation" data-source="level-up" data-type="report" data-topic="domestic-abuse femicide bereaved-families media-reporting ddw">
            <span class="nr-item-num">02</span>
            <div class="nr-item-body">
              <div class="nr-item-tags"><span class="nr-topic">Bereaved Families</span><span class="nr-topic">Media Reporting</span><span class="nr-topic">Femicide</span><span class="nr-topic">DDW Campaign</span></div>
              <h3 class="nr-item-title"><a href="https://welevelup.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/Final-LU-AAFDA-families-report.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Families Report: The Impact of Media Reporting on Families Bereaved by Domestic Homicide</a></h3>
              <p class="nr-item-meta">Level Up · 2020</p>
              <p class="nr-item-abstract">Level Up's research into the impact of media reporting on families bereaved by domestic homicide, produced in collaboration with victims' families and the charity AAFDA. The report finds that 2 in 3 families who participated said their grieving process was negatively impacted by media coverage of their loved one's death. The findings were presented to IPSO's Head of Standards in February 2020 and form a central pillar of Level Up's campaign for regulatory change.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="nr-item-end"><span class="nr-type-badge nr-type-badge--parliament">Report</span><a href="https://welevelup.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/Final-LU-AAFDA-families-report.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nr-item-link" aria-label="Open resource">↗</a></div>
          </li>

          <li class="nr-resource-item" data-tags="academic" data-source="new-statesman" data-type="academic" data-topic="domestic-abuse femicide media-reporting coercive-control women">
            <span class="nr-item-num">03</span>
            <div class="nr-item-body">
              <div class="nr-item-tags"><span class="nr-topic">Domestic Abuse</span><span class="nr-topic">Femicide</span><span class="nr-topic">Media Reporting</span><span class="nr-topic">Coercive Control</span></div>
              <h3 class="nr-item-title"><a href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/newe.12336" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Dignity for Dead Women</a></h3>
              <p class="nr-item-meta">Janey Starling, Jade Hammond · New Statesman · April 2023</p>
              <p class="nr-item-abstract">The peer-reviewed academic article by Level Up's Janey Starling and Jade Hammond, published in the New Statesman, setting out the theoretical and evidential basis for the Dignity for Dead Women campaign. The piece argues that media reporting of domestic homicide is not merely a question of taste but of public health — that inaccurate, sensationalised coverage actively impedes societal understanding of coercive control and prevents the systemic change needed to save women's lives.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="nr-item-end"><span class="nr-type-badge nr-type-badge--academic">Academic</span><a href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/newe.12336" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nr-item-link" aria-label="Open resource">↗</a></div>
          </li>

          <li class="nr-resource-item" data-tags="regulation campaign" data-source="level-up" data-type="regulation" data-topic="ipso regulation journalism-standards ddw media-reporting">
            <span class="nr-item-num">04</span>
            <div class="nr-item-body">
              <div class="nr-item-tags"><span class="nr-topic">IPSO</span><span class="nr-topic">Regulation</span><span class="nr-topic">Journalism Standards</span><span class="nr-topic">DDW Campaign</span></div>
              <h3 class="nr-item-title"><a href="https://welevelup.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/2023-Level-Up-IPSO-code-review-submission.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Level Up Submission to the 2023 IPSO Editor's Code Committee Review</a></h3>
              <p class="nr-item-meta">Level Up · 2023</p>
              <p class="nr-item-abstract">Level Up's formal submission to IPSO's 2023 Editor's Code Committee review, endorsed by the domestic abuse sector as a whole, calling for a specific sub-clause to be added to Clause 4 of the Editor's Code of Practice. The submission draws on Level Up's families research, the AIDA framework, and five years of campaign evidence to make the legal and ethical case for binding regulatory standards on reporting fatal domestic abuse. Accompanied by a petition of 26,703 signatures delivered to IPSO headquarters in March 2023.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="nr-item-end"><span class="nr-type-badge nr-type-badge--parliament">Regulation</span><a href="https://welevelup.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/2023-Level-Up-IPSO-code-review-submission.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nr-item-link" aria-label="Open resource">↗</a></div>
          </li>

          <li class="nr-resource-item" data-tags="academic" data-source="safelives" data-type="academic" data-topic="domestic-abuse femicide coercive-control women">
            <span class="nr-item-num">05</span>
            <div class="nr-item-body">
              <div class="nr-item-tags"><span class="nr-topic">Domestic Abuse</span><span class="nr-topic">Coercive Control</span><span class="nr-topic">Women</span></div>
              <h3 class="nr-item-title"><a href="https://safelives.org.uk/research-policy-library/femicide-research/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">SafeLives Femicide Research and Data</a></h3>
              <p class="nr-item-meta">SafeLives · Ongoing</p>
              <p class="nr-item-abstract">SafeLives maintains a body of research on femicide, domestic homicide, and the patterns of coercive control that precede fatal domestic abuse in the UK. Their datasets and analysis underpin much of the evidence base used by campaigners, journalists, and policymakers when discussing the scale and nature of domestic killings — including the statistic that a woman is killed by a partner or ex-partner every three days in England and Wales.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="nr-item-end"><span class="nr-type-badge nr-type-badge--academic">Academic</span><a href="https://safelives.org.uk/research-policy-library/femicide-research/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nr-item-link" aria-label="Open resource">↗</a></div>
          </li>

          <li class="nr-resource-item" data-tags="organisation" data-source="aafda" data-type="organisation" data-topic="domestic-abuse femicide bereaved-families">
            <span class="nr-item-num">06</span>
            <div class="nr-item-body">
              <div class="nr-item-tags"><span class="nr-topic">Bereaved Families</span><span class="nr-topic">Domestic Abuse</span><span class="nr-topic">Femicide</span></div>
              <h3 class="nr-item-title"><a href="https://www.aafda.org.uk/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">AAFDA — Advocacy After Fatal Domestic Abuse</a></h3>
              <p class="nr-item-meta">Organisation</p>
              <p class="nr-item-abstract">AAFDA (Advocacy After Fatal Domestic Abuse) is the UK's leading organisation providing specialist advocacy and peer support to families and friends bereaved by domestic homicide. Founded by Frank Mullane, AAFDA has been a key partner in Level Up's Dignity for Dead Women campaign — with AAFDA families contributing to both the families research report and the IPSO lobbying effort. Their work gives direct voice to those most affected by poor media coverage of domestic abuse deaths.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="nr-item-end"><span class="nr-type-badge nr-type-badge--org">Organisation</span><a href="https://www.aafda.org.uk/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nr-item-link" aria-label="Open resource">↗</a></div>
          </li>

          <li class="nr-resource-item" data-tags="organisation" data-source="women-aid" data-type="organisation" data-topic="domestic-abuse coercive-control women">
            <span class="nr-item-num">07</span>
            <div class="nr-item-body">
              <div class="nr-item-tags"><span class="nr-topic">Domestic Abuse</span><span class="nr-topic">Women</span><span class="nr-topic">Coercive Control</span></div>
              <h3 class="nr-item-title"><a href="https://www.womensaid.org.uk/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Women's Aid</a></h3>
              <p class="nr-item-meta">Organisation</p>
              <p class="nr-item-abstract">Women's Aid is the national domestic abuse charity in England, providing lifesaving services and campaigning for systemic change. Their Femicide Census — produced annually in partnership with Karen Ingala Smith — documents every woman killed by a man in the UK and is the primary statistical source for understanding the scale of domestic homicide. Women's Aid supports Level Up's calls for improved media standards in covering these deaths.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="nr-item-end"><span class="nr-type-badge nr-type-badge--org">Organisation</span><a href="https://www.womensaid.org.uk/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nr-item-link" aria-label="Open resource">↗</a></div>
          </li>

          <li class="nr-resource-item" data-tags="organisation" data-source="refuge" data-type="organisation" data-topic="domestic-abuse women femicide">
            <span class="nr-item-num">08</span>
            <div class="nr-item-body">
              <div class="nr-item-tags"><span class="nr-topic">Domestic Abuse</span><span class="nr-topic">Women</span><span class="nr-topic">Femicide</span></div>
              <h3 class="nr-item-title"><a href="https://refuge.org.uk/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Refuge — National Domestic Abuse Helpline</a></h3>
              <p class="nr-item-meta">Organisation</p>
              <p class="nr-item-abstract">Refuge is the largest UK provider of specialist domestic abuse services, running the National Domestic Abuse Helpline. They publish guidance for journalists and media organisations on how to report on domestic abuse safely and responsibly, and provide resources for survivors seeking help. Their expertise informs the evidence base underpinning Level Up's media guidelines.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="nr-item-end"><span class="nr-type-badge nr-type-badge--org">Organisation</span><a href="https://refuge.org.uk/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nr-item-link" aria-label="Open resource">↗</a></div>
          </li>

          <li class="nr-resource-item" data-tags="regulation" data-source="ipso" data-type="regulation" data-topic="ipso regulation journalism-standards media-reporting">
            <span class="nr-item-num">09</span>
            <div class="nr-item-body">
              <div class="nr-item-tags"><span class="nr-topic">IPSO</span><span class="nr-topic">Regulation</span><span class="nr-topic">Journalism Standards</span></div>
              <h3 class="nr-item-title"><a href="https://www.ipso.co.uk/editors-code-of-practice/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IPSO Editor's Code of Practice</a></h3>
              <p class="nr-item-meta">IPSO · Ongoing</p>
              <p class="nr-item-abstract">The IPSO Editor's Code of Practice sets out the standards that member newspapers and magazines must follow — and which Level Up is campaigning to strengthen with a specific clause on domestic homicide reporting. Understanding the existing Code, particularly Clause 4 (Harassment) and Clause 5 (Intrusion into grief or shock), is essential context for following Level Up's regulatory campaign and assessing what legal tools currently exist to challenge irresponsible domestic abuse coverage.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="nr-item-end"><span class="nr-type-badge nr-type-badge--parliament">Regulation</span><a href="https://www.ipso.co.uk/editors-code-of-practice/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nr-item-link" aria-label="Open resource">↗</a></div>
          </li>

          <li class="nr-resource-item" data-tags="regulation" data-source="impress" data-type="regulation" data-topic="regulation journalism-standards media-reporting">
            <span class="nr-item-num">10</span>
            <div class="nr-item-body">
              <div class="nr-item-tags"><span class="nr-topic">Regulation</span><span class="nr-topic">Journalism Standards</span><span class="nr-topic">Media Reporting</span></div>
              <h3 class="nr-item-title"><a href="https://impress.press/standards/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IMPRESS Standards Code</a></h3>
              <p class="nr-item-meta">IMPRESS · Ongoing</p>
              <p class="nr-item-abstract">IMPRESS is the UK's only independently regulated press regulator, recognised under the Royal Charter on Press Regulation. Level Up's media guidelines are endorsed by IMPRESS alongside IPSO, giving the guidelines cross-regulator backing. The IMPRESS Standards Code — which explicitly addresses reporting on vulnerable people and intrusion into grief — provides a complementary regulatory framework to IPSO's Editor's Code in assessing media coverage of domestic homicide.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="nr-item-end"><span class="nr-type-badge nr-type-badge--parliament">Regulation</span><a href="https://impress.press/standards/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nr-item-link" aria-label="Open resource">↗</a></div>
          </li>

          <li class="nr-resource-item" data-tags="journalism campaign" data-source="bbc" data-type="article" data-topic="domestic-abuse media-reporting ddw journalism-standards">
            <span class="nr-item-num">11</span>
            <div class="nr-item-body">
              <div class="nr-item-tags"><span class="nr-topic">Media Reporting</span><span class="nr-topic">DDW Campaign</span><span class="nr-topic">Journalism Standards</span><span class="nr-topic">Domestic Abuse</span></div>
              <h3 class="nr-item-title"><a href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p06k5t74" target="_blank" rel="noopener">BBC Victoria Derbyshire: Launch of Level Up's Media Guidelines</a></h3>
              <p class="nr-item-meta">BBC · 2018</p>
              <p class="nr-item-abstract">Level Up launched its original media guidelines on BBC Victoria Derbyshire in 2018, with Ryan Hart and Joanne Beverley — sister of Natalie Hemming — speaking about how irresponsible media coverage had failed their families in the aftermath of domestic homicide. The broadcast brought national attention to the campaign's call for journalists to report domestic abuse deaths with accuracy, accountability, and dignity, and marked the beginning of Level Up's engagement with newsrooms and regulators.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="nr-item-end"><span class="nr-type-badge nr-type-badge--media">Article</span><a href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p06k5t74" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nr-item-link" aria-label="Open resource">↗</a></div>
          </li>

          <li class="nr-resource-item" data-tags="journalism" data-source="guardian" data-type="article" data-topic="domestic-abuse femicide media-reporting coercive-control women">
            <span class="nr-item-num">12</span>
            <div class="nr-item-body">
              <div class="nr-item-tags"><span class="nr-topic">Femicide</span><span class="nr-topic">Media Reporting</span><span class="nr-topic">Coercive Control</span><span class="nr-topic">Women</span></div>
              <h3 class="nr-item-title"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/society/domestic-violence" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Guardian: Domestic Violence Coverage</a></h3>
              <p class="nr-item-meta">The Guardian · Ongoing</p>
              <p class="nr-item-abstract">The Guardian's dedicated domestic violence coverage provides a reference point for responsible journalism on fatal domestic abuse, including reporting that centres coercive control, names perpetrators' choices, and amplifies the voices of survivors and bereaved families. The Guardian has been one of the UK's most engaged mainstream outlets in implementing the principles underlying Level Up's media guidelines, making their coverage a useful benchmark for journalists seeking to improve their own reporting standards.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="nr-item-end"><span class="nr-type-badge nr-type-badge--media">Article</span><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/society/domestic-violence" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nr-item-link" aria-label="Open resource">↗</a></div>
          </li>

          <li class="nr-resource-item" data-tags="journalism campaign" data-source="journalism-uk" data-type="article" data-topic="ddw media-reporting training aida journalism-standards">
            <span class="nr-item-num">13</span>
            <div class="nr-item-body">
              <div class="nr-item-tags"><span class="nr-topic">DDW Campaign</span><span class="nr-topic">Training</span><span class="nr-topic">AIDA Framework</span><span class="nr-topic">Journalism Standards</span></div>
              <h3 class="nr-item-title"><a href="https://www.journalism.co.uk/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Journalism.co.uk: Resources on Trauma-Informed Reporting</a></h3>
              <p class="nr-item-meta">Journalism.co.uk · Ongoing</p>
              <p class="nr-item-abstract">Journalism.co.uk is a key professional development platform for UK journalists, providing resources and guidance on sensitive and trauma-informed reporting practices. Their coverage of domestic abuse reporting standards, training opportunities, and regulatory developments provides useful professional context for journalists seeking to implement the principles of Level Up's AIDA framework in their own newsrooms.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="nr-item-end"><span class="nr-type-badge nr-type-badge--media">Article</span><a href="https://www.journalism.co.uk/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nr-item-link" aria-label="Open resource">↗</a></div>
          </li>

          <li class="nr-resource-item" data-tags="organisation" data-source="ava" data-type="organisation" data-topic="domestic-abuse training journalism-standards">
            <span class="nr-item-num">14</span>
            <div class="nr-item-body">
              <div class="nr-item-tags"><span class="nr-topic">Training</span><span class="nr-topic">Domestic Abuse</span><span class="nr-topic">Journalism Standards</span></div>
              <h3 class="nr-item-title"><a href="https://avaproject.org.uk/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">AVA — Against Violence &amp; Abuse</a></h3>
              <p class="nr-item-meta">Organisation</p>
              <p class="nr-item-abstract">AVA (Against Violence &amp; Abuse) is the domestic abuse training and development organisation with which Level Up partnered in 2021 to develop CPD-accredited online journalist training on reporting fatal domestic abuse. AVA's expertise in domestic abuse education underpins the training content, which features testimony from survivors and victims' families and uses the AIDA framework developed by Level Up. Journalists and newsrooms can book training via mediasupport@welevelup.org.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="nr-item-end"><span class="nr-type-badge nr-type-badge--org">Organisation</span><a href="https://avaproject.org.uk/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nr-item-link" aria-label="Open resource">↗</a></div>
          </li>

          <li class="nr-resource-item" data-tags="journalism campaign" data-source="independent" data-type="article" data-topic="domestic-abuse media-reporting femicide coercive-control">
            <span class="nr-item-num">15</span>
            <div class="nr-item-body">
              <div class="nr-item-tags"><span class="nr-topic">Media Reporting</span><span class="nr-topic">Femicide</span><span class="nr-topic">Coercive Control</span><span class="nr-topic">Domestic Abuse</span></div>
              <h3 class="nr-item-title"><a href="https://www.independent.co.uk/topic/domestic-violence" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Independent: Domestic Violence Reporting</a></h3>
              <p class="nr-item-meta">The Independent · Ongoing</p>
              <p class="nr-item-abstract">The Independent has published extensive coverage on domestic abuse, femicide, and coercive control — including investigations into how newsrooms report on domestic homicides and the impact of sensationalised coverage on bereaved families and public understanding. Their journalism represents both examples of progress in the field and case studies in how mainstream media coverage of domestic abuse deaths continues to fall short of the standards Level Up's guidelines set out.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="nr-item-end"><span class="nr-type-badge nr-type-badge--media">Article</span><a href="https://www.independent.co.uk/topic/domestic-violence" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nr-item-link" aria-label="Open resource">↗</a></div>
          </li>

          <li class="nr-resource-item" data-tags="campaign regulation" data-source="level-up" data-type="campaign" data-topic="ddw ipso regulation media-reporting domestic-abuse">
            <span class="nr-item-num">16</span>
            <div class="nr-item-body">
              <div class="nr-item-tags"><span class="nr-topic">DDW Campaign</span><span class="nr-topic">IPSO</span><span class="nr-topic">Regulation</span><span class="nr-topic">Media Reporting</span></div>
              <h3 class="nr-item-title"><a href="https://welevelup.org/petition/dignity-for-dead-women/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Sign the Petition: Change the Way Press Reports Fatal Domestic Abuse</a></h3>
              <p class="nr-item-meta">Level Up · From 2018</p>
              <p class="nr-item-abstract">Level Up's petition to IPSO calling for an enforceable clause in the Editor's Code of Practice on reporting of fatal domestic abuse. First launched in October 2018, the petition has gathered over 26,700 signatures from Level Up supporters and was delivered to IPSO headquarters in March 2023, accompanied by four women who had lost mothers, sisters, and daughters to domestic homicide and Dawn Butler MP. The petition continues to gather signatures as the regulatory campaign progresses.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="nr-item-end"><span class="nr-type-badge nr-type-badge--focused">Our Campaign</span><a href="https://welevelup.org/petition/dignity-for-dead-women/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nr-item-link" aria-label="Open resource">↗</a></div>
          </li>

          <li class="nr-resource-item" data-tags="journalism" data-source="justice-gap" data-type="article" data-topic="domestic-abuse femicide coercive-control regulation">
            <span class="nr-item-num">17</span>
            <div class="nr-item-body">
              <div class="nr-item-tags"><span class="nr-topic">Domestic Abuse</span><span class="nr-topic">Femicide</span><span class="nr-topic">Coercive Control</span><span class="nr-topic">Regulation</span></div>
              <h3 class="nr-item-title"><a href="https://www.thejusticegap.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Justice Gap: Domestic Abuse and the Law</a></h3>
              <p class="nr-item-meta">The Justice Gap · Ongoing</p>
              <p class="nr-item-abstract">The Justice Gap is a UK legal journalism platform providing in-depth coverage of domestic abuse law, coercive control prosecutions, and the criminal justice response to femicide. Their reporting contextualises the legal frameworks around domestic homicide — including the Domestic Abuse Act 2021 — within broader discussions about accountability, sentencing, and the relationship between legal and media systems in shaping public understanding of intimate partner violence.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="nr-item-end"><span class="nr-type-badge nr-type-badge--media">Article</span><a href="https://www.thejusticegap.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nr-item-link" aria-label="Open resource">↗</a></div>
          </li>

          <li class="nr-resource-item" data-tags="academic" data-source="safelives" data-type="academic" data-topic="domestic-abuse coercive-control femicide women">
            <span class="nr-item-num">18</span>
            <div class="nr-item-body">
              <div class="nr-item-tags"><span class="nr-topic">Coercive Control</span><span class="nr-topic">Femicide</span><span class="nr-topic">Domestic Abuse</span><span class="nr-topic">Women</span></div>
              <h3 class="nr-item-title"><a href="https://safelives.org.uk/research-policy-library/dash-risk-checklist/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">SafeLives DASH Risk Checklist</a></h3>
              <p class="nr-item-meta">SafeLives · Ongoing</p>
              <p class="nr-item-abstract">The Domestic Abuse, Stalking, Honour-Based Violence (DASH) risk checklist is the primary professional tool used by police, social workers, and domestic abuse services in the UK to identify victims at highest risk of serious harm or murder. Understanding the DASH framework is essential context for journalists reporting on domestic homicide — particularly in cases where warning signs were present and statutory agencies failed to act — and for understanding why so many fatal domestic abuse cases were, as Level Up argues, preventable.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="nr-item-end"><span class="nr-type-badge nr-type-badge--academic">Academic</span><a href="https://safelives.org.uk/research-policy-library/dash-risk-checklist/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nr-item-link" aria-label="Open resource">↗</a></div>
          </li>

        </ol>
